WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:05.230 --> 00:00:08.390
-Welcome, everybody.

00:00:08.390 --> 00:00:12.260
I'm so happy to have you
here, friends and colleagues

00:00:12.260 --> 00:00:14.860
to Radcliffe Day 2016.

00:00:14.860 --> 00:00:16.700
And let me just say
before I get started

00:00:16.700 --> 00:00:18.950
that I know it's warm in here.

00:00:18.950 --> 00:00:22.730
And I invite you to
take off your jackets.

00:00:22.730 --> 00:00:25.560
Do whatever it takes
to be comfortable.

00:00:25.560 --> 00:00:28.930
I'm Liz Cohen, Dean of
the Radcliffe Institute.

00:00:28.930 --> 00:00:32.610
As Harvard's Institute
for Advanced Study,

00:00:32.610 --> 00:00:35.740
Radcliffe convenes
faculty and students

00:00:35.740 --> 00:00:39.910
from all of Harvard's schools
and audiences from far

00:00:39.910 --> 00:00:42.740
beyond our gates
to share inquiry

00:00:42.740 --> 00:00:47.950
into the arts, humanities,
sciences, and social sciences.

00:00:47.950 --> 00:00:51.530
That is why I am delighted
to welcome so many of you

00:00:51.530 --> 00:00:54.920
today, both here in
Cambridge and online,

00:00:54.920 --> 00:00:58.330
to join in our
annual celebration.

00:00:58.330 --> 00:01:02.820
I am especially pleased to
welcome Drew Faust, Harvard

00:01:02.820 --> 00:01:05.180
President and Founding
Dean of the Radcliffe

00:01:05.180 --> 00:01:15.290
Institute, Provost Alan
Garber, and Bill Lee, Senior

00:01:15.290 --> 00:01:21.330
Fellow of the
Harvard Corporation,

00:01:21.330 --> 00:01:24.070
along with other members
of Harvard's governing

00:01:24.070 --> 00:01:28.020
boards, the Harvard Alumni
Association, the Radcliffe

00:01:28.020 --> 00:01:31.400
Deans Advisory Council,
the Schlesinger Library

00:01:31.400 --> 00:01:34.700
Council, the Radcliffe
Associates Program, the Anne

00:01:34.700 --> 00:01:38.330
Radcliffe Society, as well as
past members of the Radcliffe

00:01:38.330 --> 00:01:42.640
College Board of Trustees
and Alumni Association.

00:01:42.640 --> 00:01:46.720
We are very excited to have a
United States Attorney General

00:01:46.720 --> 00:01:51.990
Loretta Lynch, class of 1981,
Harvard Law School, class

00:01:51.990 --> 00:02:01.620
of 1984 with us today as well.

00:02:01.620 --> 00:02:05.740
And, of course, we are
thrilled to have Janet Yellen,

00:02:05.740 --> 00:02:08.830
Chair of the Board of Governors
of the Federal Reserve

00:02:08.830 --> 00:02:18.740
as our 2016 Radcliffe Medalist.

00:02:18.740 --> 00:02:23.970
And a special welcome to former
Chair of the Fed Ben Bernanke

00:02:23.970 --> 00:02:26.530
and to Harvard Professor
of Economics Greg

00:02:26.530 --> 00:02:31.060
Mankiw for helping us pay
tribute to our guest of honor.

00:02:37.780 --> 00:02:41.390
Welcome, as well,
to the very few

00:02:41.390 --> 00:02:45.620
of you here today hoping
to get advance word on what

00:02:45.620 --> 00:02:50.400
the Fed will do with interest
rates at its June meeting.

00:02:50.400 --> 00:02:54.640
I would like to recognize
the reunion classes of 1941,

00:02:54.640 --> 00:03:08.390
'46, '51, '56, '61,
'66, '71, '76, '86, '91.

00:03:08.390 --> 00:03:10.810
Did I forget one?

00:03:10.810 --> 00:03:20.690
'81, '86, '91, '96, 2001,
2006, 2011, and our newest

00:03:20.690 --> 00:03:32.340
graduates in the class of 2016.

00:03:32.340 --> 00:03:35.310
We also welcome former
Bunting Fellows,

00:03:35.310 --> 00:03:38.020
current and former
Radcliffe Fellows,

00:03:38.020 --> 00:03:40.100
and the Harvard
undergraduates who

00:03:40.100 --> 00:03:44.440
so ably serve as our
fellows' research partners.

00:03:44.440 --> 00:03:47.660
Everyone, please join me
in congratulating members

00:03:47.660 --> 00:03:51.050
of the earliest class
represented here today,

00:03:51.050 --> 00:04:04.320
the great class of 1939.

00:04:04.320 --> 00:04:07.100
All of us gathered
under this tent

00:04:07.100 --> 00:04:11.090
